                    <span>I got this book because I was interested in learning more about Tao -- my only experience had been the Tao of Pooh.  This is probably a good book if you know about Tao and the philosophy behind it, but as a newcomer, it wasn't interesting or educational.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Marvelous!</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>9</span>
                      /
                      <span>9</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2001-06-03</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>As a long-time Chuang-Tzu enthusiast, I thoroughly enjoyed this translation.  I imagine this would be very enjoyable to the general reader; I have read many commentaries on the meaning of Chuang-Tzu's philosophy (Victor Mair's, Allinson's, Wing-Tsit Chan's, A.C. Graham's, etc.) so my perspective is "biased" in particular way- I like the absurdity and relativistic notions, sort of a Lewis Carroll point of view.  This translation fits in with my predilictions nicely.  Chuang-tzu takes some pondering, and any translation that makes it too simple is doing the reader an injustice.  This one captures all the irony and absurdity, yet leaves plenty of room for befuddlement.  It contains ALL the chapters, not just the inner ones.  Highly recommended!!  I keep this by the bed along with The People's Guide to Mexico, another perennial favorite!</span>
                  
              
